text: First of all, it's better than scraping Yahoo data. I'll start with that. Those were terrible models. But the idea is I separate into three parts of a research platform. There's obviously the data that you're going to aggregate as much information as possible, build a mosaic of publicly available information around a company. There's the tools like the computers, the code stacks of how you go about analyzing that data. So data plus analysis and putting together. And then there's the people, the team itself, who's going about utilizing the tools and the data to reach conclusions on how it goes through. So the part of those three and how they've evolved over time is everything is heading towards more sophistication. So for data, the breadth and depth of data available now is much, much higher than what we've seen in the past. So when you started back in 2004, even back at Cornell, you were dealing essentially with just copy set for the financial statements. You're dealing with pricing for CRISP. And then you're dealing with IBIS possibly for analyst estimates along the way. And those are data that's going to go back to the 1990s. 60s on a quarterly basis for the financials and 1920s for the pricing.
